and operands are grouped and the order in which value computation will occur. They do not tell us the order in which the operands or subexpressions are evaluated. The compiler is free to evaluate operandsa,b,c, ordin any order. The compiler is also free to calculatea * borc * dfirst.For most expressions, this is irrelevant. In our sample expression above, it doesn’t matter in which order variablesa,b,c, ordare evaluated for their values: the value calculated will always be14. There is no ambiguity here.But it is possible to write expressions where the order of evaluation does matter. Consider this program, which contains a mistake often made by new C++ programmers:#include <iostream>

